segments.text: He was on the shape staff, yeah.

And he had orders for our, for the 302nd Transport Wing to provide him with airlift to move French political prisoners back to France as soon as they were released from the different prison camps in Germany.
also asked that some member from our command go with him.
Colonel Bateman condescended to let me go along with him.
We went to many a camp, picked these guys up.
The U.S. Army would overrun the camp and we'd be right in behind them.
Some of them would be home back in France the very next day.
And the French were appreciative of it to the degree that that's, I know it was the reason that I was awarded the French Quarter Gear with Silver Star for the action.
I'm sure that Angel...
Since he was the lieutenant colonel at the time, he probably was given the Prince Carthagare with palm, but the degree of the Carthagare is usually determined by the rank of the person receiving it.
Tell me about the conditions in these German prison camps.
Well,
I'm going to kick that thing off in a minute.

The best way to describe the condition is probably try to describe some of the people that we pulled out of those camps that had long since given up on life and had long since, definitely long since given up ever expecting to get back to France.
I had, subsequent to that time, been through the...
camps where they imprisoned all the Jews and disposed of most of them.
I guess the next degree of just existing is probably the way the political prisoners lived because they had no reason to
execute them but they were certainly hoping that they would die and therefore no longer have to maintain them and provide for them.
The sanitary conditions were horrible.
Some of the camps that we went into,
later years have been used by US Army and US Air Forces in Germany.
It seems that once the property is taken out of the German
It's just handed down from one agent to another to use.
And how do we use it?
Denazification program?
After what?
How do we use these?
Oh, as either a location for one of our units or administrative headquarters or something like that.
So most of the French political prisoners then were just on the edge of starvation.
Right.
I'd say that 90% to 95% of them are requiring some type of assistance just to transport themselves, you know, from one place to another.
Did you go in with doctors to ?
The main thing was to move them out of the country.
not to try to medicate them where we found them, but to move them to France.
And then wherever they were offloaded in France, they were cared for.
But the main thing was to move them, to get them out of Germany post-haze and emptied up.
Because this operation was...
or at times less than a half a mile behind the moving front.
Not to try to establish something there, but as soon as they were overrun, get those poor suckers out of there and get them home.
A good question might be, who laid this on and was it all part of the effort
And I've never even really looked at that, because I'd look at it now and say it's just part of the Humanitarian Act, and it had very little to do with prosecuting the war.
And your job was transportation, then?
The range of transportation, the climate?
We called back to our unit to bring
So many birds in a certain location.
And then angels, of course, to administer to them and find out who within the organization was their titular head.
There seems to be a, though I've never been one, I've never been in the,
I have talked to many people that have been in prison when the prison was overrun or changed hands or something like that.
There seems to be some type of feeling between the guard and the person being guarded, you know, that, well, we're leaving and good luck to you and take off, you know, and not want to have animosity.
I mean, that's all over with now.
Hope you live, maybe, you know.
Was there that feeling today?
In a number of places there were, yes.
I have a friend that lives right here that was a prisoner.
And the Germans, when they got ready to leave because the Russians were coming, the Germans actually handed over to them arms and ammunition so that the US forces could keep the Russians down.
This type of thing.
Where was he a prisoner?
In Eastern Germany?
Yep.
But it had to be in the northern part because that's where the Russians were coming down.
He was on a bomb crew that went down.
Do you think there was that type of relationship between the French guards and the German guards and the French prison?
No.
No?
No.
Not politically.
No.
They'd still hope to die.
Why didn't they just shoot him?
They seemed to shoot everybody else, didn't they?
Well, under different types of control, I guess.
I don't know.
What were your feelings when you got into these bases and saw these conditions?
I don't really know.
I can't answer that.
Do you...
It doesn't take the one or two of them, and then you become kind of immune to it.
The job is to move them and help them get out of there.
There's not so much that we can do.
Once we're in, identify that they are the...
French political prisoner and not of their own people or something like that, call the taxi and get them aboard the taxi and move to the next one.
Did you feed them first?
No way would you feed them.
There's something there.
Within the camp?
Yeah.
We're just a handful of people.
Again, recognizing them, call the taxi, and send them home.
And how long did you have this job?
Well, this was a project effort.
It's September, isn't it?
No, it was just a project that went on about four to six weeks, something like that.

as fast as the army was moving we were just right behind for that period of time and this is in when probably march and april of 1945 that era at that time the war ends in may so is that right right before the end of the war then yeah it could have been as early as even in february
Why didn't they, do you know why they didn't have a French, why didn't they have French officers doing this?
Why did they have American officers?
Because they needed the transportation.
Well, the reason they didn't have an American officer from our outfit is because, you know, we had the inter-theater transport.
We were set up to do this type of work, whereas, all respect to the troop carrier, you know, they're good at loading parachutists and
and pushing people out the door, you know, in Geronimo and hanging on their cables.
But, you know, we were set up to carry passengers, to manifest people, to care for them, you know, and so on.
Now, why Angel instead of a French officer?
I don't know, other than the fact that we were behind the American Army back then.
Oh, okay, so you're in the American sector.
Yeah.
Okay, then what happened?
Then what was your next?
This is a temporary assignment, so then did you go back to Paris?
Yeah, I just went back.
The fact is, while I was gone, there's a fellow that's up at College Station now, worked for me, Jack Jones.
I don't know what department he's in up there, but...
He set in for me while I was gone.
He was the headquarters commandant.
We had worked together before.
In fact, as the war simmered down, we put this history of the 302nd Transport Wing together and had it.
Oh, did you?
You wrote that?
It's nothing but assembly of stuff.
He was the photographer on the battalion, and he did all of the photographic work.
Oh, it's horrible writing, but you've got to remember it was put together over there, and we had it reproduced and hardbacked and everything without costing anybody, and everybody got a copy of it.
That's great.
Then about that time, things really began to peter out, and
By that time the war was about over.
Yeah.
And were you interested or did you think that you'd be going to the Pacific Front?
No, I had no idea that I'd go there because of the time that I'd already spent in Europe and the
It even looked like things were beginning to get pretty good for us in the Pacific, even before they dropped the two nuke bombs.
The way that people were being relieved from Europe was based on how many points they had and how many service and all that business.
Of all things, I had gone over with a
7th Air Depot Group, and I was reassigned to an air depot group in Belgium to come home.
It was coming through the States, and all I was going to do is just ride with them and then drop off from the States.
So I went over with an air depot group, and I came back with an air depot group, and I did all the work with transport and carrying.

and not to let a guy have a free ride when i got up to the air depot group the commander called me in and called me in and he said well you're going to go home and you're on the list when we get to the states you drop off and we all take leave and we're going on the pacific
And he said, it looks like you're going to have to do some work for us.
And I said, like what?
And he says, I don't know about that.
He says, but I'm appointing you a train commander to move us from here to the port.
And I said, thanks a lot, Colonel.
And he said, well, you didn't want to sit around here.
We were right out of Lige, Belgium.
He said, you didn't want to sit around here all this time and do nothing, did you?
I said, no, sir, I want to be the train commander.
He said, all right, you're the train commander.
And so I put together a three-element move and three train loads, moved them from where they were in Lige to Camp Top Hat, I guess it was.
All of the...
camps that people were assembled at were named after cigarettes.
Can you imagine that?
Top hat.
I bet you didn't even know there was a top hat cigarette.
I don't have any smoke cigarettes, but it was one of the cigarettes that came about during the war and it was a cheapie.
Anyway, we moved the air depot group into the camp top hat.
ultimately boarded ship and came home.
And where did you land in America?
Landed at Hampton Roads, Virginia.
Was there a festival for the returning veterans or was there some kind of parade?
No.
We went into the polling camp there in Virginia.

and we were there for about two days they got us all organized and put a whole slew of us on a train headed to san antonio here fortunately there was a major on there that outranked me so that made him the train commander
At that time, they were already processing those of us that had enough points to get out, that wanted out.
And they assigned a code to everybody in the Air Corps.
I don't know about the Army.
And once recommended for regular, recommended for reserve,
Once regular, once reserved.
The one was yes, and the two was no.
And this little girl had already communicated with me and said, if this is what service is like, well, you better choose.
So my code was 1121, recommended for regular, recommended for reserved.
Didn't want regular, but did want reserved.
So got on back.
took leave after we got to San Antonio, and then I had to go back to Wright-Patterson and turn in all of the stuff that by then the Japs had given up.
So this Air Depot group stuff was all at Wright-Patterson.
We had to go back, break it out of crates, and turn it in.
And then they sent me down to
Ellington closed and sent me over to Randolph and started processing me out.
And they said, you know, if you were to stay in the service two more months, you'd get an automatic promotion to lieutenant colonel.
Well, this was in the fall of 45.
And I had 120 days leave, which pushed my termination date up to April.
But my plans were to be back in A&M
Well, the first of February, you know, when the second term started.
I said, Colonel, you're very kind.
Can you guarantee me that I will not be on a court-martial board or a board of inquiry when it's time to release me?
No, no way.
I said, I can't take it then.
I'll go ahead and get out.
I gave up.
I can't understand.
I mean, could you explain why you decided not to stay on active duty?
Yeah.
She said, there's your wife?
Yeah.
Did you want to?
Or were you ready to get out?
I think I was ready.
You were ready to get out?
Why?
Were you discouraged with it?
Or why did you want to?
I wasn't real sure of what was.
There we built up the biggest, largest fighting force that the world had ever known.
And I could see it being dumped in a hurry and not real sure that we were going to have the civilian
as well as political support behind it.
But the one thing that concerned me more than anything was the Air Corps was still the prodigal son of the Army.
We thought we were our own bosses, but we weren't.
Why didn't you lie down?
Why didn't you like that?
Why didn't I like that?
Because I had long since believed that it could have worked a hell of a lot simpler and more effective the other way around.
That air power could control where
land and sea power had gone through history and lost its position and was no longer there.
And I still believe that.
It didn't hurt.
I'd say it didn't hurt.
Yeah, it deferred promotion and advancement five or six years, but, you know, in a whole career, what, five or six years?
But if you would have stayed in until, if you would have stayed in, then for just another couple of months you would have been a lieutenant colonel.
Right.
When I did go back on active duty, I would have gone back to the lieutenant colonel, rather than .
That's the five or six years it would have saved.
At that time, you'd already made up your mind to come back to A&M and finish your degree.
Looking back, do you think it was a wise choice?
Well, yes, because I did some things in the five or six years that I would never have done that ultimately paid off in that secondary role.
If you remember, first, I wanted to be an officer.
Second, I wanted to be an engineer.
I had not really been able to be an engineer up until that time.
And I guess if you had to put it on the scale at all, it would tilt to the plus side a whole lot more than it would to the minus.
We had some very choice things happen.
The guy said, good news, bad news.
Sure, that's through life.
But this, for instance, this same angel from headquarters, he returned to Texas A&M.
And sure enough, he ended up being in a position that when I said, say, Marty and I are going to come back and we're going to be in school another term and a summer.
He says, oh, we're opening some brand new apartments.
And of course, we're talking now about right after the war.
But those wooden co-op buildings that are south of Caulfield, those all used to be co-ops where kids came from different farm communities and lived together and had a house by there.
And then they made apartments out of them.
Four apartments, two up and two down.
Boy, they were choice, brand new.
We were the first ones to go into the co-op apartment, thanks to Angel.
And he said, you got one of those apartments.
I said, how'd I get it?
He said, I put your name down.
So that's where we lived.
Again, like I said, I had this eyesight problem.
I certainly couldn't fly, but I had enough points built up in the service that while I was finishing my academics, I took a private pilot course right out there at Eastwood.
You just learn to fly.
So I would never have done that.
I had to pay for it if I'd even found the time to do it.
So I satisfied my own curiosity that I now could legally do something that I had
been doing on the slide because a lot of these guys had let me take off and land and things like that.
But now I can if I want to.
I got my license.
The only flight I ever did was again with guys that would let me take off and land in the lighter Air Force aircraft.
How had Texas A&M changed?
If you hadn't been there for now five years, and now you're coming back.
Well, I had to change.
See, I hit there right at the wave of all the vets coming back.
There were a few there that turned before me, but when I came in is when the largest bunch had come in.
Now the next, for summer, there were even more.
But everything was cold.
not co-ed, co-cadet, co-vet.
Even the, see, like I said, the editor of the battalion, they were co-editors.
One was a cadet, and I was elected as the vet editor.
And you could see it begin to have more older people, and people that had, even though they may be young, had
Been off to war for a couple years and then come in there.
Well, just the maturity alone, they were older.
Now, how long that lasted at A&M, I don't know, because I wasn't there that long.
But I guess until those going to school on the GI Bill kind of became a strict minority instead of a heavy minority.
I don't think they ever outnumbered you.
Maybe they did.
I don't know.
How are the relationships between the... No problem at all.
No problem between the vets and the court kids?
Because, you know, you have very mature people versus real young, you know, 17, 18-year-olds.
No problem.
I don't think so.
It certainly didn't surface itself during the time that...
But I had the battalion, you know, to the point where we really had to fight things out, you know, or air them in the newspapers or things like that.
No problem.
So you only had, what, 12 credits to go?
How many credits did you have?
I took one whole term, and because I was in flying, I just stayed on through the whole summer rather than get out half of the summer so that I could take the other half of the flying course.
Then we went on home.
So you graduated in August of 1946?
Yeah.
Now, at that time, when you graduated, did you consider, I know you went to work for a civilian corporation, but did you consider going back into the Air Force?
Not at that time.
So you wanted to work as an engineer.
And you did from 1946 to 1951.
That's right.
And you were also a reserve officer.
And did you go to reserve meetings?
Not regularly.
I went enough to just keep my status.
So from 1946 to 51, you were the owner-manager of Southside Construction.
Southstate, yeah.
Yeah, Southstate Construction Company.
Did you do this?
If you were the owner-manager, was this your own construction company then?
Did you establish it?
Yes.
What happened was when I came out, my dad was engaged in a number of activities.
He was a plant representative for the Lewis Shepherd Company, which manufactures material handling equipment, lift trucks, dollies, conveyor belts, things like that.
And then he decided he wanted to build some houses and sell them.
So I went to work with him for a few months.
Then he decided that he was going to get out of the business.
And I said, OK, I don't care about the materials handling, but I'll stay in the building business.
Then I went from the building business, which is straight speculating markets, and decided to go into the construction business of bidding on jobs and doing both commercial and residential work.
and found it to be very interesting.
And one of these 4-H's, Harold Lewis, he and I got together and decided that we would form a partnership.
And not only form a partnership, but because we had limited experience
that for something like six to nine months, I would go to work for one of the other larger construction firms in Houston as a superintendent running one of the jobs out on the site.
And that he would so-called run our business, but I would also work the business at night and on the weekends or whenever I would need it.
Well, that didn't work out.
I left the other firm and went back and took over the business myself.
I was running the business as the sole owner when Uncle said, hey, come on back.
Okay, so the Korean War erupts in June of 1950.
And in 1951, you were called back in the Air Force?
Yeah, I was called back in the, must have been about,
April or May of 51.
And first question they asked, do you have any government jobs?
No.
Do you have any jobs that are government subsidized or guaranteed?
It could even be a FHA house or a house being built with a VA loan on it, anything like that.
No.
How long do you think it'll take you to close your business?
Three months?
Four months?
OK, you got it.
Let us know if you need more time.
So I had to contact them and say, I need two more months.
So December, I was back in.
Now, it's amazing.
So you sold your business, or what did you do with it?
Oh, just closed it up.
I had some properties.
that didn't have any buildings on it.

And I went out and went down and inventoried all the materials we had on hand and went to the design board and designed a building with the least amount of cash required using the inventory and built the building on the property and put some renters in it and went back in the circuit.
How?
Thinking that someday you'd come back out and start it up.
I knew that if I ever went back in, I wasn't going to come out.
Then why didn't you just sell it?
What, the business?
Construction business won't sell.
Unless it's a real big thing.
It wasn't heavy construction of building highways and bridges and having an awful lot of equipment.
It was a building construction where most of your equipment is.
is owned and carried by the craftsmen rather than the company.
Oh, I had tar kettles, concrete mixers, trucks.
But at that time, there were too many what I call graduate carpenters who thought they wanted to be contractors.
And competition's pretty keen.
Now, we've got some things on there in the tape
Why didn't we get out and all this?

She actually picked up the orders and brought them out to my office, my construction office, where I did the estimating and what drawing I had to do and where I kept my inventory and opened those orders.
And I said, well, these are orders calling me back to duty.
What do you think we ought to do?

what she said i think we ought to go back and maybe i'll see more of you in the service than i have in the construction business so in that time she had completely changed her mind absolutely fantastic so are you happy to go back oh hell yes sure
By that time you were happy.
Did it have more to do with just your personal life or with the war in Korea?
No.
I knew I'd never make the war in Korea because that was already calming down by the time December of 51 came along.
In fact, in December they asked me, they said, you don't have to come if you don't want to.
I said, man, you remember that Confederate general that the heck of a get you got?
I've closed a business for six months.
I've been coming back into service.
And now you tell me I don't have to come back?
I said, you've got me.
You know.
But, no, see, by then, Korea was beginning to calm down.
It was diminishing.
I'd gotten my
My degree, I'd taken courses at the University of Houston in design, civil engineer courses that later helped me towards my master's degree.
And I had accomplished all that really that I wanted to do.
And I knew that I could run a business.
As a major general once said,
I don't have two guys on my staff that have ever made a payroll.
Everybody else had come out of school and gone into the military, and all they'd seen was that side of the line.
But one other colonel and I, we'd made payrolls.
We'd suffered.
We knew what cash flow was.
We knew what contractors were going through.
Again, that's this human side that I spoke of earlier.
The more exposure you can get and the more different walks of life, the better you are.
And that's what I say.
The accounting graduate just doesn't have it as compared to that guy at A&M that can get himself in all types of exposure if he wants to.
Well, we went in, and it took a while to get
Again, engineering and the service, but this time I was bound and determined.
I was not going to be pushed off in the administrative or personnel side, even though I was called back as a personnel staff officer because that's what I was when I went out.
It hadn't changed.
That's what I was when I came back.
So we were sent to Warner Robins, Georgia,
to headquarters of a numbered air force and administering to the reserve personnel.
And after a few months of plowing the ground over there and personnel and then agent general's job, the local personnel people
Well, I called on the general, the commanding general, which is a protocol type thing to do.
When he found out that I was an engineer and I'd been in the construction business, he liked to have a history.
He said, boy, you'd be in my office tomorrow morning.
We're going to get that straightened out.
Well, out of courtesy, I went by because I had friends that were in the personnel business.
I went by and I said, hey, yeah, we've heard about it, but just relax.
Nothing's going to happen.
What do you mean nothing's going to happen?
I'm going in there.
Yeah.
Went in and he had changed.
Turned out I outranked his engineer, so he wasn't about to do anything.
So I said, okay, we've got to go around that one.
If the general's not going to move me into engineering because I outrank his man, then
What are we going to do next?
So this headquarters, since it administered to the reserve personnel, administered to the ROTC program.
And I just went over and I said, where do you have openings for our engineer officers in the ROTC program?
He says, Auburn and Texas A&M.
I said, only Auburn.
I want the one at Texas A&M.
And they said, you'll never get it.
I said, why?
They said, they won't let you go.
I said, well, all we can do is try.
Well, I put in an application to go.
It was turned down locally, which meant that it had to go to the next higher headquarters.
And the next headquarters concurred with the turn down, which meant it had to go to Washington, to the top headquarters.
And Washington
Reversed it.
It says the Continental Air Command and the 14th Air Force will fulfill its share of assignments to the ROTC program.
Application approved.
How?
Well, if I go to Texas A&M to teach civil engineering, Air Force type.
Then it was called Air Installation Zone.
Now, why did it even go up?
Why wasn't it just killed right there on the level?
Because any disapproval has to have a concurrence.
Oh, I see.
And since it was a straight concurrence of the disapproval, it was subject to Air Force review.
So all of a sudden, there I am.
And I'm at A&M.
A&M in the position to teach air installation.
And guess what?
They changed the curriculum from specialized curriculum
of communications officer, installations officer, supply officer, administrative officer, to a generalized curriculum where everybody was taught the same thing.
So for three years I sat there and taught, still not teaching engineering, but in a slot calling for an engineer officer.
And that's what really made the difference.
I was in the slot even though I wasn't teaching engineering.
I was in the slot.
The Air Force thought that you were, this is what the Air Force thought.
Yeah.
They thought that you were teaching engineering.
Yeah.
And that's how you got into engineering in the Air Force finally.
When I left A&M, I went up to, do you know where Mineral Wells is?
I've heard of it.
It's up out of Fort Worth, west of Fort Worth.
And we used to have an air base up there, but the aviation engineers were located there at Walters Air Base.
Then the Army later took it over and trained helicopter pilots there.
And I went up to be in the aviation engineer force, and from there I went on at the end of the engineers.
Now, the...

The assignment there at A&M, of course, proved quite fruitful because I was able to get my master's in civil and without incurring any federal funds to pay for it and without me incurring an obligation, a service obligation.
Of course, that wouldn't bother me.
If the service sends you to school and you
inherit an obligation to serve so many years.
But that didn't bother me.
So you pretty much went on a night school?
No.
They didn't have night school at that time.
I went maybe two courses a semester.
And then in the summer, a course, just one or two at a time.
Of course, I had steel design, concrete design, and estimating that they transferred from the University of Houston that I had gotten after my bachelor's degree.
I used to sit there and envy those other troops that were also going to school, taking education.
P.E.
and things like that.
A master's in engineering is just like a bachelor's in engineering.
They don't let up all the hours in the lab hours that you've got to put in.
But I had a real good boss.
He just said, you make all your classroom hours and your platform hours and be on time.
